description.plain:
“Sea Calls Me Home” is the fifth track on Julia Holter’s Have You In My Wilderness.

[“Sea Calls Me Home” is] about moving away from things that trap you, the scary wonder in discovering freedom.

A Claire Marie Vogel-directed video was released on September 9th.

annotations:
I can’t swim, it’s lucidity, so clear
 I can’t swim, it’s lucidity, so clear
 I can’t swim, it’s lucidity, so clear

Even though the sea calls her home, her swimming inability hardens the journey. It’s a metaphor for the difficulty of regaining a sense of home. The destination’s liberating, but getting there will be scary.

Yet, the sea’s lucid, or clear, to Julia. Despite her difficulties, she can freely perceive her challenges. It doesn’t make it easy, but it beats mindboggling comfort.

annotations:
Figures pass so quickly that I realize
 My eyes know very well
 It’s impossible to see
 Who I’m waiting for in my raincoat

Holter said in an interview for the Guardian the album title reflects ideas about relationships.

Some of her songs, she explains, are about characters saying: “Come be in my wilderness, come be in my world, don’t you want me to take you and be in my world?”

In other words, they are about that moment you give yourself over to someone else and then can’t see the wood for the trees.

Figures pass so quickly that I realize
 My eyes know very well
 It’s impossible to see
 Who I’m waiting for in my raincoat

Holter said in an interview for the Guardian the album title reflects ideas about relationships.

Some of her songs, she explains, are about characters saying: “Come be in my wilderness, come be in my world, don’t you want me to take you and be in my world?”

In other words, they are about that moment you give yourself over to someone else and then can’t see the wood for the trees.

Can I feel you? Are you
 Mythological?

The narrator is often or not amazed by their subtle and silent relationship. It puts their love’s true nature into question.

The feelings she acquires through her lover can either feel magical or non-existent at times. She revels in treating their romance as being more passionate than it is. On the other hand, the relationship feels ‘mythological’ in terms of it being like a fairy tale creature: not real.

I’m hopeful for
 The rush-hour car stares and
 The memory of your piano

The narrator wishes for the “rush hour car”; most likely meaning a car during the long haul home during rush hour.

It becomes only her lover and her, long period stares and silence together. While these moments aren’t particularly romantic in a sense, she sees the intimacy of simply sharing silent moments and wondering off with a person that is close to you.

She also is hopeful for the “memory of your piano”, another particular and personal moment between her and her lover.

These lines describe the soft and subtle intimacy of their relationship – from the silence of long car rides to the play of a piano piece.

Is it time to dance? I’ll fall
 You know I like to fall

Similarly to the beginning lines, the narrator cites a disjointed phrase and then suddenly describes something she likes to do.

She asks if it’s time to dance, and then states she will ‘fall’, and she likes to fall.

From these and the beginning lines, we can infer the narrator lives an sporadic and loose lifestyle. One minute she could be dancing to any quick beat and the next she’s falling and losing control – but she likes it – and so does her lover.

She likes to fall – in love.

A good reason to go
 You know I love to run away from the sun

The narrator enjoys these constant rainy days, and dislikes when it’s actually sunny.

Ironically, most would find this a negative factor in wanting to visit another city, citing rain as a constant annoyance. However, for some reason, the narrator thoroughly enjoys it.

She revels in the rainy and bleak, and runs away from the always sunny and bright.

My first thought was there are
 So many days of rain in Mexico City

Mexico City is known for its constant rain. On average during the Summer, it rains about once every day.

This weather intrigues Julia. She enjoys a warm, rainy day feeling – a cool, melancholic warmth to most – and it gives her cover for romantic encounters, as her raincoat testifies.

description.plain:
Holter tells me about the song Silhouette, inspired by a story about two sisters obsessively waiting for their lover – the same lover – to return, though she’d rather I didn’t publish exactly where it’s from.

– From an interview by The Guardian

For example, it could be the Sweet Valley High twins, as the series happens in California, to match with Holter’s location.

annotations:
Mysteries that wake up late
 The table’s set and the painting of his face
 No time to hesitate
 I cede all my light and play abandoned fool

This is a scene of a failure of language; a relationship on the verge of a breakdown. And even though on surface it seems to be going through a routined motion, the lack of love and romance is apparent which is hurting Julia.

Language is such a play
 He called his exit, but his eyes irresolute
 What pasts still sit today?
 I feel I’m walking around in blue
Julia is able to see through the use of language here and can rightfully understand where the relationship stands.
